post_text: We have received notification from the Iowa Department of Education that we are able to begin using summer lunch protocol. This will allow all students ages 18 and under to participate in the school breakfast and lunch programs at no cost. We will begin this as of Thursday, September 10th. This is a temporary change and will continue until December 31st or until federal funding for the summer lunch program is exhausted. Due to the fact that we do not know how long the program will run, we will not be issuing refunds of deposited lunch money.

post_text:
A Note to our Elementary Families:
The school year is rapidly approaching, and we are excited to get your students back in school!
We have Mini-conferences scheduled for September 2 & 3. If you have not signed up, you can do so at https://www.myconferencetime.com/gces/. If you prefer to do the conference virtually, sign up for conferences and then contact your child's teacher via email. You may bring your child to conferences with their school materials to meet the teacher. Masks are highly encouraged for the mini-conferences.
As you know some supplies are in short supply, and if you would like to donate some, it would be greatly appreciated. We are in need of hand sanitizer and clorox-type wipes.
Also, we are requesting that each child in grades K-4 have an art supply bag. This was not on the original supply list. The art supply bag should consist of 24 count crayons, 8 count markers, scissors (K-2nd should get round tipped scissors), 2 glue sticks, 1 large eraser, 3 pencils, and a box/bag to put it in (a gallon ziplock is fine).

post_text:
At their August 19th meeting, the Greene County School Board approved a mask requirement matrix. Starting the year, all buildings will be at “Green” and masks will be highly encouraged.
If certain marks are reached, we will move to “Yellow” and masks will be required if social distancing is not possible. We also could move to “Red” which would mean that masks will be required even if social distancing is possible. The matrix will be administered for each school independently (one building may be yellow and another may be green). Along with this matrix, it is important to note that masks will be required in band and vocal music classes involving singing and playing instruments. There will also be additional mask requirements for extra-curricular activities. Below is a link to the matrix.

https://drive.google.com/file/d/1Kuv9oyMMcNYiOwpKRFWBIne3RjrxsZgF/view

Due to delays with furniture installation, the first day of High School will be moved back until Monday, August 31st. The Open House originally scheduled for August 22nd will be moved back one week to Saturday, August 29th.

The Greene County High School and Career Academy will be open for a limited walk through by the public on Saturday, August 29th from 12:30 PM to 3:30 PM.

Due to the current conditions related to COVID-19 combined with preparation for high school classes starting on August 31st, not all rooms and areas will be available for the public to walk through. In addition, anyone taking part in the walk through will be required to wear a mask and sanitize their hands upon entering the building.

Preliminary plans are being made for a more formal open house and dedication at a later date as allowed by recommendations and guidelines related to COVID-19.

post_text:
The Greene County Schools recently finished a three week summer school program for students in grades Kindergarten through 8th grade. 101 students participated in summer school. They were served by 17 teachers and 11 associates that allowed for the students to be broken into smaller learning groups and at times be given one-on-one attention. A school counselor was on site every day to address social emotional needs of students and a school nurse was at summer school every day as well to take care of health related concerns.

Students worked on following social distancing guidelines and washed/sanitized their hands frequently. Although the summer school session was shorter than normal, it provided an opportunity for students to get back into the swing of doing schoolwork and also provided the school an opportunity to put into practice many of the protocols it will be using when school starts later this fall.

We want to thank everyone that took part in summer school as well as everyone that worked to make summer school a success.

post_text:
Friday, July 17
10 Tips for an elementary (or any) parent:
*Go to Open Houses and Parent Teacher Conferences
*Visit the school website (find lunch calendars, staff contact information, etc.)
*Support Homework Expectations
*Send your Child to School Ready to Learn (well rested, needed supplies, fed)
*Teach Organizational Skills (keep bag, shoes, homework ect. in assign place)
*Teach Study Skills (break down large tasks into smaller, help them study)
*Know and Understand School Policies
*Get Involved
*Take Attendance Seriously

text:
Friday, July 17
10 Tips for an elementary (or any) parent:
*Go to Open Houses and Parent Teacher Conferences
*Visit the school website (find lunch calendars, staff contact information, etc.)
*Support Homework Expectations
*Send your Child to School Ready to Learn (well rested, needed supplies, fed)
*Teach Organizational Skills (keep bag, shoes, homework ect. in assign place)
*Teach Study Skills (break down large tasks into smaller, help them study)
*Know and Understand School Policies
*Get Involved
*Take Attendance Seriously
*Make Time to Talk about School (Tell me 3 good things about your day. Tell me 2 things you learned. What did you do at recess? - instead “How was your day?”)

post_text:
Thursday, July 16
Create an EXIT PLAN with your middle school and high school student. As your preteen or teenager starts becoming more independent they may find themselves in situations they want to get out of but don’t know how. Establish a secret code or word that they can text you when they want out of a situation. Your job is to get them out of that environment or situation and NOT ASK QUESTIONS. If they use the Exit Plan and then get drilled with questions, they likely will never use it again. The goal is for your teenager to know they can always depend on you to get them home safe.

post_text:
Just a quick reminder that Greene County CSD will resume with a modified summer lunch program on June 8th.

Although the Governor has given the okay for school districts to open up buildings for summer school and summer lunch, we still have several details (social distancing, transportation, etc.) to work out to make this a reality. It is our goal to be able to have details worked out so we can start up with the onsite serving of meals by the end of June. Until that time, we will be serving sack lunches from the Grand Junction Community Center (11:30 - 11:50), Rippey Community Center (12:00 - 12:15), Scranton Community Center (11:30 - 11:50), and the Greene County Middle School (11:30 - 12:30). We will only be serving lunch (not breakfast). Children/students will be required to pick up the meals. We will not hand out meals to adults and will not give multiple meals to any one person.

post_text:
First, this is a reminder that the current school lunch distribution program will end on May 28th. We will resume with a modified summer lunch program on June 8th.

Although the Governor has given the okay for school districts to open up buildings for summer school and summer lunch, we still have several details (social distancing, transportation, etc.) to work out to make this a reality. It is our goal to be able to have details worked out so we can start up with the onsite serving of meals by the end of June. Until that time, we will be serving sack lunches from the Grand Junction Community Center (11:30 - 11:50), Rippey Community Center (12:00 - 12:15), Scranton Community Center (11:30 - 11:50), and the Greene County Middle School (11:30 - 12:30). We will only be serving lunch (not breakfast) and children/students will be required to pick up the meals. We will not hand out meals to adults and will not give multiple meals to any one person.

shared_text:
Greene County High School
May 19 at 8:17 AM ·

Five Greene County/Paton Churdan seniors took the Seal of Biliteracy exam May 8th-12. The students that participated in the exam were: Sophia Ausberger, Kaleb Fisher, Emily Hofer, Kassie Lamoureux, and Angelica Moody. All five passed which will earn them a seal stamp on their transcripts and a medal. Governor Reynolds signed Senate File 475 into law in 2018 which recognizes students who have obtained proficiency in two or more languages. There are four sections of the test: speaking, reading, writing and listening. Students must score at least INTERMEDIATE LOW in all four sections to be granted the seal. This seal allows employers to identify those who are competent in two or more languages. We are extremely proud of the extra work students put into the test! They are all very deserving of this accomplishment!

post_text:
Read below for a message from Superintendent Tim Christensen on Grab and Go Lunches at GCCSD:

I want to commend the Greene County Food Service Staff as well as the Greene County Instructional Associates and all others that have been helping cook, hand out, and deliver meals during our current crisis. All of them are doing a fantastic job. What started out with 274 meals on day one has reached 600+ on April 16th. In order to continue to provide meals efficiently and effectively, we are going to have to put some guidelines in place moving forward. We will be limiting pick up of meals to a maximum of two families per vehicle. Individual daycares will be required to pick up their own meals. We will also be trying something different the next two Fridays. We will be providing a “Take and Bake” meal with Friday, April 24th being pizza. Instructions on how to bake the meals will be included on the packaging.

post_text:
Grab and Go - Sack Lunches

Beginning Monday, March 23rd, the Greene County Schools will be providing a Grab and Go - Sack Lunch program. The program will be similar to summer lunch and is open to children living in Greene County ages 0-18 and Greene County School students. The program will run

Monday - Friday for three weeks during the current closure. Serving sites will include the Greene County Middle School, Grand Junction Community Center, Rippey Community Center, and Scranton Community Center. Participants will drive up in front of each location and staff will be handing out sack lunches from 11:30 - 1:00.

Although it is not a requirement for participation, we would ask that anyone that thinks they will be taking advantage of this program complete a participation survey which will give us a better idea of the number of meals to prepare as we want to be able to serve everyone that wants to participate. The survey can be found at bit.ly/gcgrabandgo

COVID-19 Guidance from Iowa Department of Education

“The Iowa Department of Education will be leading efforts to coordinate directly with school districts to provide clear guidance and support for Coronavirus planning and decision making for schools.

It is important to note that the Iowa Department of Public Health is not currently advising any school closures. In coordination with the Department of Public Health, the Department of Education is finalizing identification of key decision points needed to contain and mitigate COVID-19 and included in these decision points will be triggers and metrics on how we will recommend if school closures are necessary.”

post_text: Speech Contest News - All state speech contests set for Saturday, March 14 have been cancelled. The All-State Festival on March 30 at UNI is also being cancelled. These changes were made for the health and safety of our students, coaches, judges, and host schools. The IHSSA agrees that safety is the number one priority. The Executive Committee believes that the dramatic changes over the last 24 hours and the ever changing landscape surrounding the COVID-19 virus warranted cancellation of the state contests. The Executive Committee discussed and reviewed comments and concerns that were sent in by our member schools in the past few days.

post_text:
✏️PK Registration Day is April 2, 2020🎨
If your child turns 4 years old by September 15, 2020, and you live in the Greene County School District, your child qualifies for our free 4 year old PK. For children that turn 3 years old by September 15, 2020, and live in the Greene County School District, our tuition 3 year old preschool is available. If you have children that would be the age for either program, please call 515-386-3178 so that we have your contact information.
PK Registration for both programs will be on Thursday, April 2nd, between 5:00 and 7:00 pm. This is a come-and-go event. Come at a time that works in your schedule. There will be stations for you to get everything done so that your child is ready to start school in the fall.
Please bring your child’s birth certificate and social security card as we will make copies to keep in their secure cumulative file. There will be childcare provided in one of the PK rooms.
Please let us know if you have any questions.

We look forward to having your child in school! Thanks!

post_text:
JUNIOR CLASS CHILI SUPPER INFORMATION
Friday, January 17, 2020

Our Junior Class Chili Supper will be held on Friday, January 17, 2020, at the Elks Lodge. The Greene County High School girls’ and boys’ basketball teams will host Gilbert for a MEGA night in the Greene County Middle School Gym and the Greene County Community Center. The Hall of Fame induction will take place in between games.

Serving time for the chili supper is 5:00 p.m. to 7:00 p.m. The meal includes a bowl of chili, crackers, relishes, pie or dessert, and milk or coffee. Tickets are $6.00 each for ages six and above; five and under are free. Chili refills are $1.00 and milk refills are $.50. If you would like your meal delivered to your home, please contact Teresa Green at 386-2188.

We are excited to have Greene County High School’s Jazz Band and Director Wes Anderson perform two times between 5:15 p.m. and 6:15 p.m.

All proceeds from the Junior Class Chili Supper will go toward our 2020 “Golden Gala” prom. The banquet and dance will be held at the Wild Rose Event Center on April 4, 2020.

post_text: Tuesday, October 29, we turn Greene County Purple. Everyone in Greene County was encouraged to wear something purple or to wear a purple ribbon to raise public awareness about working to end domestic violence against men, women, and their children. The purple ribbon is a visible gesture of support for survivors and victims of domestic violence. A group of those supporting the cause had a picture taken at the Greene County High School.

post_text: Have you heard the good news? Greene County Elementary has been selected as the beneficiary of the HyVee reusable bag program that supports local non-profits! Each time a Reusable Bag is purchased at the Jefferson Hy-Vee during the month of November we will receive a $1 donation. The Reusable Bags are located on displays around the store and at the checkout. For more information about the program, please visit hy-vee.bags4mycause.com.

post_text: For safety and liability reasons, students in grades K-5 need to be accompanied by a parent/guardian in order to be admitted to football games. Students in K-4 need to be seated in the bleachers with parents/guardians. The south bleachers are reserved for students in grades 5-8. Students in 5-8 grade are expected to sit in the south bleachers or in the main bleachers and not be playing behind the bleachers.
